{"title_page": "Anton Muttukumaru", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Refimprove|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= Anton Muttukumaru\n|birth_date= 6 July 1908\n|death_date= 2001 (aged 93)\n|birth_place= [[Ceylon]]\n|death_place= Australia\n|image=Maj Gen Mutukumaru.jpg\n|caption=Major General Anton Muttukumaru\n|nickname=\n|allegiance= Ceylon\n|serviceyears= 1934\u20131959\n| servicenumber    = \tO/50001 <!--Do not use data from primary sources such as service records.--> \n|rank=[[Major General]]\n|branch= [[File:Flag of the Ceylon army (1949\u20131966).jpg|25px]] [[Ceylon Army]]\n|commands=[[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Ceylon Army]],<br />[[Chief of Staff]] of the Ceylon Army\n|unit=[[Ceylon Light Infantry]]\n|battles=[[World War II]]\n|awards=[[Order of the British Empire]]<br /> (Military Division),<br /> [[Efficiency Decoration]], <br /> [[War Medal 1939\u20131945]], <br />[[Ceylon Armed Services Long Service Medal]]\n|laterwork=[[High Commissioner]] to Australia, [[Pakistan]] and <br />Ambassador to [[Egypt]]\n}}\n[[Major General]] '''Anton M. Muttukumaru''', [[OBE]], [[Efficiency Decoration|ED]], [[Aide-de-camp|ADC]], [[Imperial Defence College|idc]] (6 July 1908 \u2013 2001) was the first Ceylonese Army officer to serve as [[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Ceylon Army]] (now [[Sri Lankan Army]]), a post he held from 1955 to 1959. He also served as Ceylon's High Commissioner to Australia, New Zealand, Pakistan and Ambassador to Egypt.<ref name=Past>{{cite web|title=Past Army Commanders |url=http://www.army.lk/pastcommanders.php |publisher=Sri Lanka Army |accessdate=17 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120830175533/http://www.army.lk/pastcommanders.php |archivedate=30 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn to Dr. Philip Marian Muttukumaru and Mary Mount Carmel Alles, he and his siblings were brought up by their mother after the early death of their father. Educated at home by an English governess and then at [[St. Joseph's College, Colombo]], he then entered [[Ceylon University College]] and in 1928, he left for [[Jesus College, Oxford]] to read Philosophy, Politics and Economics. After completing his degree, he read for the Bar and was called by [[Gray's Inn]] to become a [[Barrister]]. After returning to Ceylon, he took his oaths as an Advocate of the Supreme Court of Ceylon.<ref name=\"Island01\">{{cite news |last1=[[Henry Athukorale|Athukorala]] |title=A man among men |url=http://www.island.lk/2008/07/20/features9.html |accessdate=30 August 2019 |publisher=Island}}</ref>\n\n==Military career==\n===Ceylon Defence Force===\nAfter returning from England, in 1934 he joined the [[Ceylon Defence Force]], a part-time [[Military reserve force|reserve force]] raised by the British to defend the island. Muttukumaru was commissioned as a [[second lieutenant]] in the [[Ceylon Light Infantry]] (CLI) on 11 September 1934. IN 1939 he was mobilised with the rest of the CDF at the outset of [[World War II]]. During this time, he would go on to command the CLI Guard at the [[South East Asia Command]] headquarters in [[Kandy]] and was promoted [[Captain (land and air)|captain]] on 29 November 1940 and major in 1942. On 1 November 1943 he was promoted [[lieutenant colonel]] and appointed commanding officer, 2nd Battalion CLI, in which appointment he continued to serve until the general demobilisation which took place after the war in January 1947. He led Ceylon's contingent in the London [[victory parade]] in 1946.<ref name=\"Island01\"/>\n\nAfter the war, Muttukumaru worked once again as a lawyer representing the [[Attorney General]], in a variety of cases but soon gave up law to function as Officer in Charge, Administration in the Ceylon Defence Force Headquarters, where he assisted in the initial plans for the formation of a new Ceylon Army, including the drafting of the Army Act.<ref name=\"Island01\"/>\n\n===Ceylon army===\nWhen the Ceylon Army was formed in 1949, he was one of three lieutenant colonels commissioned into the regular force with the serial no O/50001. There he served as the [[chief of staff]] to [[Brigadier]] [[James Roderick Sinclair, 19th Earl of Caithness|the Earl of Caithness]]. During this time he attended the [[Senior Officers' School]], where he was taught by [[Field Marshal Montgomery]] and made friends with the future Israeli Defence Minister [[Brigadier]] [[Moshe Dayan]]. He lead the Ceylon's contingent of soldiers to London on ceremonial duties for the funeral of George VI in 1952, and for the Queen's coronation. There his men mounted guard at Buckingham Palace. He was subsequently attached to [[British Army]] in  West Germany, having been attachment to the Headquarters of the [[British Army of the Rhine]].<ref name=\"Island01\"/>\n\nOn 1 January 1954, he was promoted to the rank of Colonel took over as [[commanding officer]] of the 1 Battalion, Ceylon Light Infantry and [[officer commanding]] Troops, [[Panagoda Cantonment|Panagoda]]. Under his command the battalion undertook its first live fire exercise ''Ex TYRO''. On 19 July 1954, he was appointed [[aide-de-camp]] to the Queen. On 8 February 1955, he relinquished command of the Ceylon Light Infantry. On 9 February 1955, he was promoted to the rank of [[Brigadier]] and appointed first Ceylonese Army Commander. This took place while he was at attending the [[Imperial Defence College]], Colonel [[H. W. G. Wijeyekoon|Wijeyekoon]] who was the chief of staff, served as acting army commander until his return in 1956 when he assumed command of the army. On 1 January 1958, he was promoted to the rank of [[Major General]], becoming the first army officer to hold the rank. During his time as commander, the army grew in size and was deployed on several occasions to curb civil unrest and riots. He elevated the Army Recruit Training Depot at [[Diyatalawa]] to the Army Training Centre, raised a new infantry battalion, [[Ceylon Sinha Regiment]], promoted all commanding officer to the rank of Lieutenant Colonel after elevating all regular units to regimental strength; established the Headquarters of the Ceylon Volunteer Force and initiated the concept of regional commands. In 1959, he decided to retire so that younger officers could have their chance to command, even though Prime Minister [[Solomon Bandaranaike]] asked him to stay on.<ref name=\"Island01\"/>\n\nFor his contributions to Ceylon, he was made an officer of the [[Order of the British Empire]] (Military Division) and awarded the [[Efficiency Decoration]] for volunteer service in the CDF. For wartime service, he had earned the [[War Medal 1939\u20131945]], and for service in the Ceylon Army, he received the [[Ceylon Armed Services Long Service Medal]], the [[Queen Elizabeth II Coronation Medal]] and the [[Ceylon Armed Services Inauguration Medal]].<ref name=\"Island01\"/>\n\n==Later years==\nAfter leaving the army, Muttukumaru was appointed Ceylon's High Commissioner to Pakistan (with concurrent responsibility for Afghanistan, Iran and Iraq) in 1959, and High Commissioner to Australia and New Zealand from 1963 to 1966. Later in 1966, Muttukumaru became Ambassador to Egypt, concurrently he was Ambassador to Jordan, the Sudan and Yugoslavia. He permanently retired in 1969. In 1996, the [[General Sir John Kotelawala Defence University|General Sir John Kotelawela Defence Academy]] awarded an 'Honourable [[Doctor of Letters]]' to him for his contributions to the buildup of the Army and for being the first to publish a short history of the Army, \"The Military History of Ceylon \u2013 An Outline\" ({{ISBN|81-7013-046-8}}). General Muttukumaru died in Australia in 2001 at the age of 93.<ref name=\"Island01\"/>\n\n==Family==\nMuttukumaru married Margaret Vasanthi Ratnarajah in 1944. They had three sons: Anton Vasantha Muttukumaru, Philip Rajkantha Muttukumaru and Christopher Peter Jayantha Muttukumaru, [[Order of the Bath|CB]].<ref name=\"Island01\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Sri Lankan Non Career Diplomats]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080419082404/http://www.army.lk/index1.php Official Website of Sri Lanka Army]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110605181225/http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2008/07/27/plus09.asp First Ceylonese Commander of the Army]\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1315323/Maj-Gen-Anton-Muttukumaru.html Maj-Gen Anton Muttukumaru]\n* [http://www.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~lkawgw/gen7016.html Muttukumaru ancestry]\n* [http://sundaytimes.lk/991010/news2.html Deserters are cowards, says first Sri Lankan Army Chief]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Ceylon Army]]\n | before=[[Francis Reid|F.S. Reid]]\n | after=[[H. W. G. Wijeyekoon]]\n | years=1955\u20131959}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Commanders of the Sri Lankan Army}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Muttukumaru, Anton}}\n[[Category:1908 births]]\n[[Category:2001 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan generals]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan Tamil lawyers]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan Tamil military personnel]]\n[[Category:High Commissioners of Sri Lanka to Australia]]\n[[Category:High Commissioners of Sri Lanka to New Zealand]]\n[[Category:High Commissioners of Sri Lanka to Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Sri Lanka to Egypt]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Sri Lanka to Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Sri Lanka to Iran]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Sri Lanka to Iraq]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Sri Lanka to Jordan]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Sri Lanka to Sudan]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Sri Lanka to Yugoslavia]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Sri Lankan Tamil descent]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan Tamil diplomats]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan emigrants to Australia]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Ceylonese Officers of th